result.execSummary:
The defendant Mickie A. Georgeson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Resisting/Failing to Stop/Fleeing, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.04(2t).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: (Incompetency)

Defendant Mickie A. Georgeson in court with attorney Adam Raabe.  Michael X. Albrecht appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Parties have reviewed the report of the doctor.  State gives status.  Request 30 review after defendant has completed the program of regaining competency.  State waives opportunity to have further testimony.  Court to rely on the report.  Attorney Raabe believes proceedings should be suspended.  Defendant not likely to restore during statutory time limits.  Further decision making a concern as well.  Court finds, based on the report, defendant is not competent to proceed.  Report is not clear on timeline of regaining, if at all.  Refer defendant to outpatient restoration program. Report within 45 days from program completion.
